![image.png](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/92ec4438-ad2b-4ad6-bab3-900c6101f219_1761729883.1773283.png)

You are given n men and n women. Each man has a ranked preference list of all n women, and each woman has a ranked preference list of all n men. The goal is to find a stable matching, which is a pairing of all n men and n women such that no two people would prefer to be with each other over their current partners.

A pair (m,w) is considered unstable if:

m prefers some other woman w′ over his current partner w.

w′ also prefers m over her current partner.

Your task is to implement an algorithm that finds a stable matching for any given set of preferences.

Example:

Let n=2.
Men: M_1,M_2
Women: W_1,W_2

Preferences:

M_1: W_1, W_2

M_2: W_2, W_1

W_1: M_2, M_1

W_2: M_1, M_2

Input:

men_preferences = {
    "M1": ["W1", "W2"],
    "M2": ["W2", "W1"]
}
women_preferences = {
    "W1": ["M2", "M1"],
    "W2": ["M1", "M2"]
}
Output:

[("M1", "W2"), ("M2", "W1")]
Explanation:

M_1 is paired with W_2. Even though he prefers W_1, W_1 prefers her partner M_2 over M_1, so no instability exists.

M_2 is paired with W_1. He prefers her to his other option, and she prefers him to her other option. This is a stable pair.

Constraints:

1≤n≤50

All preference lists are complete and unique.

General Solution for n x n: The Gale-Shapley Algorithm
The most common and effective solution for the stable marriage problem is the Gale-Shapley algorithm. It guarantees a stable matching in polynomial time (O(n2)).

Algorithm Steps:
Initialization: All men and women are considered free.

Proposals: The algorithm proceeds in rounds. In each round, every free man proposes to the most-preferred woman on his list to whom he has not yet proposed.

Responses:

If a woman receives a proposal from a man she is currently free, she accepts and becomes engaged to him.

If a woman is already engaged but receives a proposal from a man she prefers over her current fiancé, she accepts the new proposal and jilts her current fiancé. The jilted man becomes free again.

If a woman receives a proposal from a man she considers less desirable than her current fiancé, she rejects his proposal.

Termination: This process continues until every man is engaged. The algorithm is guaranteed to terminate because in each step, at least one man proposes to a woman he has not yet proposed to, and no man ever proposes to the same woman twice. The final set of engaged pairs is a stable matching.

Why it Works:
The algorithm is "male-optimal" because it guarantees that every man gets the best possible partner he could get in any stable matching. This is because men propose in order of preference. If a man gets rejected by a woman, he knows it's because she found someone she prefers more, and he can't do better than his final partner. The reverse is true for women, making the algorithm "female-pessimal." However, a stable matching is always found.

Example: 3x3 Case with More Input/Output
Let's consider n=3.
Men: M_1,M_2,M_3
Women: W_1,W_2,W_3

Preferences:

M_1: W_1,W_2,W_3

M_2: W_2,W_1,W_3

M_3: W_1,W_2,W_3

W_1: M_2,M_1,M_3

W_2: M_1,M_2,M_3

W_3: M_1,M_2,M_3

Step-by-step execution:

Round 1:

M_1 proposes to W_1. W_1 is free, so she accepts. Pair: (M_1,W_1).

M_2 proposes to W_2. W_2 is free, so she accepts. Pair: (M_2,W_2).

M_3 proposes to W_1. W_1 is already engaged to M_1. She checks her list: she prefers M_2M_1M_3. She rejects M_3.

Round 2:

M_3 is the only free man. He proposes to his next choice, W_2.

W_2 is engaged to M_2. She checks her list: she prefers M_1M_2M_3. She rejects M_3.

Round 3:

M_3 is still free. He proposes to his next choice, W_3.

W_3 is free. She accepts. Pair: (M_3,W_3).

All men are now engaged. The algorithm terminates.

Final Output:
The stable matching is: [("M1", "W1"), ("M2", "W2"), ("M3", "W3")]

Code C++ 

#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
#include <string>
#include <map>
#include <list>

// Function to find a stable matching using the Gale-Shapley algorithm
std::map<std::string, std::string> stableMatching(
    const std::map<std::string, std::list<std::string>>& men_preferences,
    const std::map<std::string, std::list<std::string>>& women_preferences) {

    int n = men_preferences.size();
    
    // Tracks men who are currently free
    std::list<std::string> free_men;
    for (const auto& pair : men_preferences) {
        free_men.push_back(pair.first);
    }
    
    // Tracks current engagements (woman -> man)
    std::map<std::string, std::string> engagements;
    
    // A mapping from a woman's name to a map of men and their ranks.
    // This allows for O(1) lookup of a man's rank on a woman's preference list.
    std::map<std::string, std::map<std::string, int>> women_ranks;
    for (const auto& pair : women_preferences) {
        int rank = 0;
        for (const auto& man : pair.second) {
            women_ranks[pair.first][man] = rank++;
        }
    }

    while (!free_men.empty()) {
        std::string man = free_men.front();
        free_men.pop_front();

        // Get the first woman on his preference list he hasn't proposed to yet
        std::string woman = men_preferences.at(man).front();

        // Remove the proposed woman from the man's preference list
        const_cast<std::map<std::string, std::list<std::string>>&>(men_preferences).at(man).pop_front();

        // If the woman is free, she accepts the proposal
        if (engagements.find(woman) == engagements.end()) {
            engagements[woman] = man;
        } else {
            // Woman is already engaged. Check her preference for the new suitor.
            std::string current_fiance = engagements[woman];
            
            // If she prefers the new man (lower rank), she accepts his proposal
            if (women_ranks[woman][man] < women_ranks[woman][current_fiance]) {
                // Jilt the current fiance, who becomes free
                free_men.push_front(current_fiance);
                // Accept the new proposal
                engagements[woman] = man;
            } else {
                // She prefers her current fiance, so the new man remains free
                free_men.push_front(man);
            }
        }
    }

    // Convert engagements from woman->man to man->woman for a clearer output format
    std::map<std::string, std::string> final_matching;
    for (const auto& pair : engagements) {
        final_matching[pair.second] = pair.first;
    }

    return final_matching;
}

int main() {
    // Example from the problem description (3 men, 3 women)
    std::map<std::string, std::list<std::string>> men_preferences = {
        {"M1", {"W1", "W2", "W3"}},
        {"M2", {"W2", "W1", "W3"}},
        {"M3", {"W1", "W2", "W3"}}
    };
    
    std::map<std::string, std::list<std::string>> women_preferences = {
        {"W1", {"M2", "M1", "M3"}},
        {"W2", {"M1", "M2", "M3"}},
        {"W3", {"M1", "M2", "M3"}}
    };

    std::map<std::string, std::string> final_couples = stableMatching(men_preferences, women_preferences);

    std::cout << "The final stable matching is:" << std::endl;
    for (const auto& pair : final_couples) {
        std::cout << pair.first << " is paired with " << pair.second << std::endl;
    }

    return 0;
}

# Mindtickle SDE Intern Interview Experience – Pune (35K/month)

**Role:** SDE Intern  
